    "summary": "Mahavira (c. 599–527 BC, traditional dates; or c. 540–468 BC by some scholars) was the 24th and last Tirthankara ('ford-maker,' a spiritual teacher who crosses the ocean of suffering) of the Jain tradition, and the figure who systematized and propagated the religion into its enduring form. Born into a noble Kshatriya family in Bihar, he renounced his life at age 30, practiced extreme asceticism for 12 years, achieved kevala jnana (omniscience/enlightenment), and spent the remaining 30 years teaching before his death at Pavapuri.\n\nMahavira's teachings form the core of Jain doctrine: ahimsa (non-violence toward all living beings) as the supreme ethical principle; anekantavada (many-sidedness of truth, avoiding absolute assertions); aparigraha (non-possessiveness); and the path to liberation through rigorous ethical conduct and ascetic practice. Jainism's commitment to non-violence has been its most influential contribution to Indian and world thought — Mahatma Gandhi cited Jain traditions of ahimsa as a formative influence on his philosophy of nonviolent resistance. Jainism remains a living tradition with approximately 4-5 million adherents, concentrated primarily in western India, known for their extraordinary commitment to non-violence extending to the smallest insects.",
